==Controversy and criticism==
[[Image:WBC2006 Daisuke Matsuzaka.jpg|thumb|The posting system was criticized after the [[Boston Red Sox]] paid a total of $103.1&nbsp;million to sign pitcher [[Daisuke Matsuzaka]].]]
The system received criticism from MLB insiders and US sports writers after the 2006&ndash;07 posting period. Before the posting of the period's first player, [[Daisuke Matsuzaka]], in early November 2006, it was believed that he would draw bids as high as $30&nbsp;million&mdash;more than twice the bid amount that [[Ichiro Suzuki]] garnered.<ref name="kurkjian">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=kurkjian_tim&id=2697354&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab3pos2 |title=Posting process needs to be altered |author=[[Tim Kurkjian|Kurkjian, Tim]] |accessdate=January 20, 2009 |work=[[ESPN The Magazine]] |date=December 16, 2006}}</ref> Shocking both American and Japanese baseball executives, Matsuzaka received a high bid of $51.1&nbsp;million.<ref name="Sloan">{{cite web |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUSSP15866320070201 |title=Japan player posting system needs review, say Yankees |accessdate=January 20, 2009 |author= Sloan, Dan |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=February 1, 2007}}</ref> The Boston Red Sox's winning bid was more than $11&nbsp;million higher than the second largest bid.<ref name="kurkjian"/>

When the negotiations between Matsuzaka and the Red Sox had reached a stalemate as the negotiation period neared its close, ''[[The Washington Post]]''{{'s}} Dave Sheinin questioned both parties' intentions. Sheinin believed that the Red Sox could have foreseen the contractual stalemate and submitted a high bid simply to deny the [[New York Yankees]] an opportunity to negotiate with Matsuzaka. On the other hand, after Matsuzaka's agent, [[Scott Boras]], threatened to take Matsuzaka back to NPB if his price was not met, Sheinin theorized that Boras intentionally wanted to hinder contract negotiations.<ref name="Washington Post">{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/12/AR2006121201349_pf.html |title=Red Sox' Talks With Matsuzaka at Endpoint |accessdate=February 2, 2009 |author=Sheinin, Dave |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=December 13, 2006}}</ref> ''[[ESPN The Magazine]]'''s [[Tim Kurkjian]] described the situation as "the most obvious [[chicken (game)|game of chicken]] ever."<ref name="kurkjian"/> Sheinin suggested that, if the negotiations were to fail, Boras could take legal action. He could allege that by requiring MLB teams to pay large transfer fees to NPB teams, the posting system artificially depresses a player's compensation. Boras did not believe that the transfer fee should affect a player's compensation.<ref name="Washington Post"/>

The Boston Red Sox eventually signed Matsuzaka, however; Including the transfer fee and contract, the team paid approximately $103.1&nbsp;million in total to acquire the pitcher. Kurkjian believes that with fees and contracts this high, small-market teams cannot afford to compete with large-market teams for the rights to negotiate with some posted Japanese players. Kurkjian blames the posting system's employment of a blind bidding system as the cause of Matsuzaka's "outrageous offer."<ref name="kurkjian"/> He also postulates that Matsuzaka's high bid amount helped to inflate the bids for [[Kei Igawa]] who was posted two weeks later, perpetuating the problem further.<ref name="kurkjian"/> After winning the negotiation rights to Igawa, Yankees' [[General manager (baseball)|general manager]] [[Brian Cashman]] told reporters that "the posting system, clearly with what took place this winter, might not necessarily be the best system". Kurkjian claims that other MLB executives already believe that a traditional [[free agent]] structure where the highest bidder wins would be better than the current system.<ref name="kurkjian"/> MLB's vice president for Asia said that a review of the posting system would be conducted in conjunction with the NPB.<ref name="Sloan"/>

